eu.europa.ec.eurostat.jgiscotools.changedetection

Class ChangeDetection

  • java.lang.Object
    • eu.europa.ec.eurostat.jgiscotools.changedetection.ChangeDetection

  • public class ChangeDetection
extends Object
    Analyse the differences between two versions of a dataset. Compute the difference. Note: both datasets are suppose to have a shared stable identifier.
    Author:
    julien Gaffuri

      • compare

        public static Feature compare(Feature fIni,
                              Feature fFin,
                              double res,
                              List<String> attributesToIgnore)
        Compare two versions of the same feature. Both features are expected to have the same identifier and the same structure (list of attributes). The changes can be either on the attribute values, or on the geometry.
        Parameters:
        fIni - The initial version
        fFin - The final version
        attributesToIgnore -
        res - The geometrical resolution of the dataset. Geometrical changes below this value will be ignored.
        Returns:
        A feature representing the changes.

      • getHausdorffGeomChanges

        public Collection<Feature> getHausdorffGeomChanges()
        A collection of features representing the geometrical changes. For each feature whose geometry has changed, a segment representing the hausdorff distance between the initial and final geometries is created. This feature allows assessing the magnitude of the geometrical change.
        Returns:

      • findIdStabilityIssues

        public static Collection<Feature> findIdStabilityIssues(Collection<Feature> changes,
                                                        double resolution)
        Detect among some changes the ones are are unecessary: The deletion and insertion of features with very similar geometries. This happen when id stability is not strictly followed.
        Parameters:
        changes - The changes to check.
        resolution - The spatial resolution value to consider two geometries as similar.
        Returns:
        The collection of unecessary changes.
